      <hedline>
        <hl1>Virus vs. Bug</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from systems engineer Joe Lombardi says if half the effort made on combating Year 2000 computer bugs had been made on pre-empting attacks by computer viruses, Melissa and 'I Love You' viruses would have been less devastating (May 9 article)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I find it ironic that we spent so much time mitigating the risk associated with the Y2K bug, which was small compared with the risk of virus attacks (front page, May 9). This is particularly true for Windows-based systems.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I find it ironic that we spent so much time mitigating the risk associated with the Y2K bug, which was small compared with the risk of virus attacks (front page, May 9). This is particularly true for Windows-based systems.</p>
        <p>Had we spent half the time and effort we spent on Y2K pre-empting attacks from the Melissa and ''I love you'' viruses, how much better off would we be today? How much money in lost productivity would have been saved?</p>
        <p>JOE LOMBARDI  Toms River, N.J., May 9, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is a systems engineer for the Navy.</p>
      </block>
